<body>
    <h1>Wiring an Outlet with Multiple Sets of Wires</h1>

    <div class="warning">
        <strong>Warning:</strong> Working with electrical wiring can be dangerous. If you're not comfortable or experienced with electrical work, please consult a licensed electrician. Always turn off the power at the circuit breaker before beginning any electrical work.
    </div>

    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>When wiring an outlet with multiple sets of wires, you're typically dealing with a situation where the outlet is in the middle of a circuit, and power needs to continue to other outlets or fixtures. This guide will walk you through the process step-by-step.</p>

    <h2>Materials Needed</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Screwdriver (flathead and Phillips)</li>
        <li>Wire strippers</li>
        <li>Electrical outlet</li>
        <li>Wire nuts</li>
        <li>Electrical tape</li>
        <li>Voltage tester</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Step-by-Step Guide</h2>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 1:</span> Turn off the power</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Locate the circuit breaker for the outlet you're working on and turn it off.</li>
            <li>Use a voltage tester to confirm that the power is off at the outlet.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 2:</span> Remove the old outlet</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Unscrew the outlet cover plate and the screws holding the outlet in place.</li>
            <li>Carefully pull the outlet out of the box, keeping the wires intact.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 3:</span> Identify the wires</p>
        <ul>
            <li>You'll likely see two sets of wires: one coming in and one going out.</li>
            <li>Each set should have a black wire (hot), a white wire (neutral), and a bare copper or green wire (ground).</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 4:</span> Connect the ground wires</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Twist the bare copper or green ground wires together.</li>
            <li>Connect them to the green ground screw on the outlet.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 5:</span> Connect the neutral wires</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Twist the white neutral wires together.</li>
            <li>Connect them to the silver screw(s) on the outlet.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 6:</span> Connect the hot wires</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Twist the black hot wires together.</li>
            <li>Connect them to the brass screw(s) on the outlet.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 7:</span> Secure the connections</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Ensure all wire connections are tight and secure.</li>
            <li>Wrap electrical tape around the screws and bare wires for added insulation.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 8:</span> Install the new outlet</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Carefully push the wires back into the electrical box.</li>
            <li>Screw the outlet into place.</li>
            <li>Attach the cover plate.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
        <p><span class="step-number">Step 9:</span> Restore power and test</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Turn the circuit breaker back on.</li>
            <li>Use a voltage tester to ensure the outlet is working correctly.</li>
            <li>Test the outlet by plugging in a lamp or other device.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>Wiring an outlet with multiple sets of wires is a common task in home electrical work. By following these steps carefully, you can safely install a new outlet that continues the circuit to other parts of your home. Remember, if you're ever unsure or uncomfortable with any step in the process, it's best to consult a professional electrician.</p>
</body>
